{"action": "input", "code": "def color_rows_below_red(r: int, l: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Colors the rows below the red horizontal line in blue, with the length of line in the row next to r and below r\n    being 1 less than l, and the length in each row below being 1 less than the row above it.\n\n    Args:\n    - r: an integer representing the index of the red horizontal line\n    - l: an integer representing the length of the red horizontal line\n    - input_grid: a 2D numpy array representing the input grid\n\n    Returns:\n    - a 2D numpy array representing the updated grid\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(r + 1, input_grid.shape[0]):\n        input_grid[i, :l - 1] = blue\n        l -= 1\n    return input_grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    r, l = find_red_horizontal_line(input_grid)\n    above = color_rows_above_red(r, l, input_grid)\n    out = color_rows_below_red(r, l, above)\n    return out\ndef find_red_horizontal_line(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the index and length of a red horizontal line in the input grid.\n\n    Args:\n    - input_grid: a 2D numpy array representing the input grid\n\n    Returns:\n    - a tuple of two integers representing the index and length of the red horizontal line\n    \"\"\"\n    red_line = np.where(input_grid == red)[0]\n    index = red_line[0]\n    length = len(red_line)\n    return (index, length)\ndef color_rows_above_red(r: int, l: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Colors the rows above the red horizontal line in green, with the length of line in the row next to r and above r\n    being 1 more than l, and the length in each row above being 1 more than the row below it.\n\n    Args:\n    - r: an integer representing the index of the red horizontal line\n    - l: an integer representing the length of the red horizontal line\n    - input_grid: a 2D numpy array representing the input grid\n\n    Returns:\n    - a 2D numpy array representing the updated grid\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(r):\n        input_grid[i, :l + 1] = green\n        l += 1\n    return input_grid", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    r,l = `the input is a 2D numpy array, find the index and length of red horizatal line in the grid, the line may not use all pixels in the same row.`(input_grid)\n    above = `color the rows above r in green, the length of line in the row next to r and above r should 1 more than l, then the length in each row above should be 1 more than the row below it, return the grid, the length in a row means the first length pixels in the row`(r, l, input_grid)\n    out = `color the rows below r in blue, the length of line in the row next to r and below r should 1 less than l, then the length in each row below should be 1 less than the row above it, return the grid, the length in a row means the first length pixels in the row`(r, l, above)\n    return out\n    ", "gpt_code": "def color_rows_below_red(r: int, l: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Colors the rows below the red horizontal line in blue, with the length of line in the row next to r and below r\n    being 1 less than l, and the length in each row below being 1 less than the row above it.\n\n    Args:\n    - r: an integer representing the index of the red horizontal line\n    - l: an integer representing the length of the red horizontal line\n    - input_grid: a 2D numpy array representing the input grid\n\n    Returns:\n    - a 2D numpy array representing the updated grid\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(r + 1, input_grid.shape[0]):\n        input_grid[i, :l - 1] = blue\n        l -= 1\n    return input_grid\ndef find_red_horizontal_line(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds the index and length of a red horizontal line in the input grid.\n\n    Args:\n    - input_grid: a 2D numpy array representing the input grid\n\n    Returns:\n    - a tuple of two integers representing the index and length of the red horizontal line\n    \"\"\"\n    red_line = np.where(input_grid == red)[0]\n    index = red_line[0]\n    length = len(red_line)\n    return (index, length)\ndef color_rows_above_red(r: int, l: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Colors the rows above the red horizontal line in green, with the length of line in the row next to r and above r\n    being 1 more than l, and the length in each row above being 1 more than the row below it.\n\n    Args:\n    - r: an integer representing the index of the red horizontal line\n    - l: an integer representing the length of the red horizontal line\n    - input_grid: a 2D numpy array representing the input grid\n\n    Returns:\n    - a 2D numpy array representing the updated grid\n    \"\"\"\n    for i in range(r):\n        input_grid[i, :l + 1] = green\n        l += 1\n    return input_grid", "holes": {"color_rows_below_red": "color the rows below r in blue, the length of line in the row next to r and below r should 1 less than l, then the length in each row below should be 1 less than the row above it, return the grid, the length in a row means the first length pixels in the row", "find_red_horizontal_line": "the input is a 2D numpy array, find the index and length of red horizatal line in the grid, the line may not use all pixels in the same row.", "color_rows_above_red": "color the rows above r in green, the length of line in the row next to r and above r should 1 more than l, then the length in each row above should be 1 more than the row below it, return the grid, the length in a row means the first length pixels in the row"}}
